Hi Jim!
Here's a copy of the msg I sent to Mark Isaak re tectonics.  I haven't gotten
a reply from him yet, but he writes frequently on rec.games.frp so I have hope.

(Sent to imagen!isaak@decwrl.dec.com 2 pm, 24 Aug 88)

In article 2284 of rec.games.frp you wrote (re mapping a world):
> Path: vlsi!ll-xn!ames!pasteur!agate!ucbvax!decwrl!sun!imagen!isaak
> From: isaak@imagen.UUCP (Mark Isaak)
> 2)  Randomly divide your globe into 20 or so tectonic plates of various
> sizes.  Make about 1/4 of them continental plates and the rest ocean.
> Add half a dozen hot spots for flavor.
> 3)  Give your plates random directions and velocities and let 'em rip.
> Keep track of the mountain ranges, trenches, archipelagos, etc. which are
> formed in the process.
> 4)  After 100,000,000 year's worth of movement (or so), modify the directions
> and velocities and move the plates around some more.  Remember to erode the
> mountains which were made previously.  Repeat this process five or six times
> until you get a world you like.

Hey, I'm really interested in doing this.  Could you give me a little
more detail?  I've done some reading on plate tectonics but I could never
quite figure out how to make this work.  I'd like to write a computer
program that generates real-looking worlds using this technique.  The
main thing that interests me is applying the technique to planets that
are not like Earth - larger, smaller, different % water, etc.

I can handle dividing the globe up into plates.  Can you really just assign
random directions and speeds?  It gets really messy to keep track of
when things keep crawling over the poles, etc.

Dave

